snippet.textDisplay: Boy do I got a request with a story behind it. All my life, my dad has loved sweet and sour soup. Once my parents got divorced, and my dad was working on his doctorate, and would be up late at night and forget to eat, I’d make him sweet and sour soup so that he’d eat something and also know I was cheering him on. I now live on my own but Julien, I would love it if you made some sweet and sour soup, a little shout out to all the dads during this scary time to remind us to all look out for each other. If you do this, thank you. If you don’t, I understand and have an amazing day and take care of yourself mate.

snippet.textDisplay: The bread dough needs to be knead, then rested, then knead again and THEN rolled /shaped a bit and then be put in the baking form. It sounds time consuming  but its not really. Knead means massaging and rolling the dough repetedly. It helps activate the yeast even more and helps to bind the ingredients even better. Letting it rise for a few hours AFET putting into a baking form is essential. If not it might me very compact and doughy even after baking. It looked wonderful but i hope my tips help.
